## Using Zeppelin for Data Science Tasks: Data Ingestion, Data Formatting, Exploratory Analysis and Model Building.


Data Science involves a typical sequence of tasks: aquiring data, cleaning it, analyzing it for relationships, and then building a model. Zeppelin allows you to do all these from one unified interface.

import org.apache.spark.mllib.linalg.Vectors
import org.apache.spark.mllib.regression.LabeledPoint
import org.apache.spark.mllib.regression.LinearRegressionModel
import org.apache.spark.mllib.regression.LinearRegressionWithSGD
import org.apache.spark.mllib.regression.StreamingLinearRegressionWithSGD
import org.apache.spark.sql.SQLContext

case class TruckData(eventTime: Long, truckId: Int, driverId: Int, driverName: String,
                                       routeId: Int, routeName: String, latitude: Double, longitude: Double,
                                       speed: Int, eventType: String, foggy: Int, rainy: Int, windy: Int, congestionLevel: Int, isViolation: Int)
//case class WindowedDriverStats(driverId: Int, averageSpeed: Int, totalFog: Int, totalRain: Int, totalWind: Int, totalViolations: Int)
//case class TruckData(driver: Int, avgSpeed: Float, fogEvents: Int, rainEvents: Int, windEvents: Int, violations: Int, timestamp: Long)

val truckData = sc.textFile("hdfs:///tmp/trucking/data/truckEvents/part-*")

//Print raw input
println("\nRaw input data:")
truckData.take(5).foreach(println)
System.out.println("\n")

//Create a Dataframe
val truckRDD = truckData.map(_.split('|'))
    .map(atts => {
        var eventType = atts(9)
        var isViolation = 0
        if(!eventType.equals("Normal"))
            isViolation=1
        TruckData(atts(0).toLong, atts(1).toInt, atts(2).toInt, atts(3), atts(4).toInt, atts(5), atts(6).toDouble, atts(7).toDouble, atts(8).toInt, atts(9),
        atts(10).toInt, atts(10).toInt, atts(12).toInt, atts(13).toInt, isViolation)
        })
val truckDf = truckRDD.toDF()
truckDf.show()


truckDf.registerTempTable("truckingEvents")

## Let's do some Exploratory Data Analysis so that we have a better grasp on the nature of this data set.

paragraphs.text:
%sql

select driverName, sum(isViolation)/count(*) as avgViolations, avg(speed) as avgSpeed, avg(foggy) as avgFog, avg(rainy) as avgRain, avg(windy) as avgWind, avg(congestionLevel) as avgCongestion from truckingEvents group by driverName order by avgViolations desc limit 10

%sql

%sql

%sql

select congestionLevel, sum(isViolation)/count(*) from truckingEvents  group by congestionLevel

%sql

select latitude, longitude, eventType, foggy from truckingEvents where isViolation > 0 and foggy = 1 group by latitude, longitude, eventType, foggy
